            <fr:addr>jms-0183</fr:addr>
            <fr:route>http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0183.xml</fr:route>
            <fr:title text="Decompilation of NFAs">Decompilation of <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017H.xml" title="Non-deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017H" type="local">NFA</fr:link>s</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Corollary</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Any <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0185.xml" title="Automatical language" addr="jms-0185" type="local">automatical</fr:link> <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016M.xml" title="Formal language" addr="jms-016M" type="local">language</fr:link> is <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>14</fr:day></fr:date><fr:addr>jms-0183/0</fr:addr><fr:route>http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0183/0.xml</fr:route><fr:title text="" /><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <html:p>We have shown in <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0180.xml" title="Generalised NFA decompilation" addr="jms-0180" type="local">Lemma <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-0180" /></fr:link> that each <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0182.xml" title="The formal language accepted within a region" addr="jms-0182" type="local">regional langauge</fr:link> of an <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017H.xml" title="Non-deterministic finite automaton" addr="jms-017H" type="local">NFA</fr:link> is <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link>; <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular languages</fr:link> are closed under finite unions, so it suffices to decompose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> into a finite union of regional languages <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}_{M}{\mathopen {}\left (q,S,q'\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>

 <html:p>We note that if a <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-016I.xml" title="String over an alphabet" addr="jms-016I" type="local">string</fr:link> is accepted by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex>, it does so by means of a path from the starting state to some accepting state; each of these scenarios for a given accepting state specifies a <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-0181.xml" title="Region of an NFA" addr="jms-0181" type="local">region</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (s_{M},Q_{M},q\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q\in F_{M}]]></fr:tex>. Therefore, we immediately deduce:</html:p>

 <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[
  \mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}} =
  \bigcup _{q\in F_{M}}
  \mathcal {L}_{M}{\mathopen {}\left (s_{M},Q_{M},q\right )\mathclose {}}
 ]]></fr:tex>

 <html:p>Therefore it follows that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}{\mathopen {}\left (M\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-017Y.xml" title="Regular language" addr="jms-017Y" type="local">regular</fr:link>.</html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
